<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Getting Started / Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        An overview of the Urban Chaos Storyboard Editor interface, map view, file controls, districts, and missions.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        The Storyboard Editor
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Storyboard Editor is a simple editor for creating and modifying <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.sty</Run> storyboard files. These files define the districts and missions shown on the Urban Chaos overworld map.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Districts are the larger areas shown on the overworld map. Missions are the individual playable missions that appear under those districts.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_full_window.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Map View
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The main map view displays the overworld map. District markers are shown on this map so you can see where each district appears in the storyboard screen.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Selecting a district on the map allows you to inspect the missions associated with that district.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_map_view.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Status Bar
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        At the bottom of the window is the <Bold>status bar</Bold>. Like the other Urban Chaos editors, this shows the current status and provides feedback when files are opened, saved, edited, or exported.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_status_bar.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        File Menu
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The File menu contains the main commands for creating, opening, and saving storyboard files.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_file_menu.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">New <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+N)</Run></Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Creates a new storyboard file and loads the standard overworld image.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Open</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Opens an existing <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.sty</Run> storyboard file.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Save</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Saves the currently loaded storyboard file.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Save As</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Saves the current storyboard file to a new location.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Quick Action Toolbar
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The quick action toolbar provides fast access to common file commands and shows a summary of the currently loaded storyboard file.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_quick_actions.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>New</Bold> — creates a new storyboard.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Open</Bold> — opens an existing <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.sty</Run> file.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Save</Bold> — saves the current storyboard.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>A running tally of <Bold>Districts</Bold> and <Bold>Missions</Bold> in the currently loaded file.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Management Bar
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The right-hand management bar is where districts and missions are created and edited. It contains two tabs: <Bold>Districts</Bold> and <Bold>Missions</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_management_bar.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Districts Tab</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Used to add, edit, position, and delete district entries. Districts represent the larger areas shown on the overworld map.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Missions Tab</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Used to add, edit, template, and delete mission entries. Missions are the individual mission items that appear under districts.</Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Viewing Existing Storyboard Files
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A good way to understand how storyboard entries are structured is to open an existing <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.sty</Run> file.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Select <Bold>File → Open</Bold>, choose a storyboard file, and inspect how the districts and missions are listed in the management bar.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Storyboard%20Editor;component/Help/Images/storyboard_getting_started_open_existing_sty.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>Before creating a new storyboard from scratch, open an original game storyboard file and study how district IDs, mission IDs, unlocks, mission files, audio files, and briefing text are organised.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a new storyboard or open an existing <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.sty</Run> file.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add or edit districts in the <Bold>Districts</Bold> tab.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add or edit missions in the <Bold>Missions</Bold> tab.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Assign each mission to a district and configure its unlock requirements.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save the completed storyboard file.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Continue to <Bold>Managing Districts</Bold> to learn how to create district entries, position them on the map, and associate missions with them.
    </Paragraph>

</FlowDocument>
